## 4. Inbound mapping — Claude Code → canonical

Claude Code has **two telemetry paths**:

- **Path A (Hook)** — our CLI plugin sits in `~/.claude/plugins/openlit-cc/` and is invoked on every PreToolUse / PostToolUse / SessionStart / SessionEnd / UserPromptSubmit / Stop / SubagentStop hook event. We emit `coding_agent.*` spans the same way we do for Cursor.
- **Path B (Native)** — Claude Code's `CLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_TELEMETRY=1` makes Claude Code itself emit OTel metrics + events + (with `CLAUDE_CODE_ENHANCED_TELEMETRY_BETA=1`) spans, all under `claude_code.*` and `service.name=claude-code`.

OpenLit accepts both. The query layer coalesces. The hard rule on attribute mapping:

### Path A: hook adapter (`cli/internal/coding/hook/claudecode/handle.go`)

| Claude Code hook payload key | Canonical attribute | Notes |
| -- | -- | -- |
| `session_id` | `coding_agent.session.id` | |
| `transcript_path` | `claude_code.transcript.path` (extras) | so we can re-tail in the UI later |
| `cwd` | `code.cwd` | resource attribute, cached |
| `hook_event_name` | `coding_agent.hook.event` | |
| `permission_mode` | `coding_agent.policy.permission_mode` | resource attribute |
| `tool_name` | `gen_ai.tool.name` | |
| `tool_use_id` | `gen_ai.tool.call.id` | |
| `tool_input` | `gen_ai.tool.call.arguments` | full mode only |
| `tool_response` | `gen_ai.tool.call.result` | full mode only |
| `source` (SessionStart) | `claude_code.session.source` (extras) | `startup` / `resume` / `continue` |
| `reason` (SessionEnd) | maps to outcome enum (see §7) | |
| Transcript tail (last N KB) | session token + cost totals | bounded by `tailfile.Tail` |

The hook adapter MUST stamp `coding_agent.signal_source = "hook"` on every span it emits.

### Path B: native Claude Code telemetry

Claude Code emits its own OTel signals with `service.name = "claude-code"`. We accept it raw. The query layer coalesces both schemas. For symmetry, the canonical equivalents are:

| Claude Code native attribute | Canonical attribute | Notes |
| -- | -- | -- |
| `session.id` | `coding_agent.session.id` | also: `OTEL_METRICS_INCLUDE_SESSION_ID=1` |
| `app.version` | `coding_agent.client.version` | enable with `OTEL_METRICS_INCLUDE_VERSION=1` |
| `user.email` | `gen_ai.user.name` + `gen_ai.request.user` | resource-level |
| `user.account_uuid` | not mapped — kept as Anthropic identifier | |
| `organization.id` | mapped to `gen_ai.organization.id` if set | for org filtering |
| `terminal.type` | `terminal.type` | already aligned |
| `model` (cost metric) | `gen_ai.request.model` | |
| `claude_code.cost.usage` (metric) | `coding_agent.session.cost_usd` (on session span) | metric-to-attribute mapped at query time |
| `claude_code.token.usage` (metric, by `type`) | `gen_ai.usage.input_tokens` / `output_tokens` / `cache.read_input_tokens` / `cache.creation_input_tokens` | |
| `claude_code.session.count` (metric) | session count rollup | derived |
| `claude_code.lines_of_code.count` (metric) | `coding_agent.edit.lines.added` / `removed` | summed per session |
| `claude_code.commit.count` (metric) | derived UI counter | no canonical attr — `gen_ai.user.commit_count`? Out of scope for v1. |
| `claude_code.pull_request.count` (metric) | derived UI counter | same |
| `claude_code.active_time.total` (metric) | `coding_agent.session.active_time_seconds` (future) | not yet wired |
| `claude_code.user_prompt` event | `coding_agent.llm.turn` span, `kind=prompt` | |
| `claude_code.tool_result` event | `coding_agent.tool.call` span | |
| `claude_code.api_request` event | `coding_agent.llm.turn` span, `kind=response` | carries cost/tokens |
| `claude_code.api_error` event | `coding_agent.llm.turn` span, `errored=true` | |
| `claude_code.tool_decision` event | `coding_agent.edit.decision` span when tool ∈ {Edit, Write, NotebookEdit, MultiEdit} | otherwise dropped |
| `claude_code.permission_mode_changed` event | `coding_agent.session.permission_mode_changed` event | |
| `claude_code.compaction` event | `coding_agent.session.loop.compact` event | |
| `claude_code.api_retries_exhausted` event | `coding_agent.llm.turn.retry_exhausted` event | |
| `claude_code.mcp_server_connection` event | `coding_agent.mcp.connection` event | |
| `claude_code.skill_activated` event | `coding_agent.skill.activated` event | |
| `claude_code.plugin_loaded` / `plugin_installed` event | dropped at v1 | not modelled |
| `claude_code.auth` event | dropped at v1 | not relevant to coding-agent analytics |
| `claude_code.feedback_survey` event | dropped at v1 | |
| `claude_code.internal_error` event | dropped at v1 | not user-actionable |

Native spans (when traces beta is on) are accepted as-is and joined into our model via the **inbound coalesce in the query layer** (§5). We do NOT rewrite spans at the collector.

The native path's `signal_source` is `native`. We infer this in the query layer:

```sql
multiIf(
  SpanAttributes['coding_agent.signal_source'] = 'hook', 'hook',
  ResourceAttributes['coding_agent.signal_source'] = 'hook', 'hook',
  SpanName LIKE 'claude_code.%' OR ResourceAttributes['service.name'] = 'claude-code', 'native',
  ResourceAttributes['service.name'] = 'cursor' AND mapContains(ResourceAttributes, 'coding_agent.session.id'), 'hook',
  ''
) AS signal_source
```

## 5. Query-layer coalesce — the dual-path rule

When both paths are active for the same Claude Code session, we get two writers landing telemetry under the same `session.id`. We dedupe at read time:

### Session-level rollup (cost, tokens, model)

```text
authoritative_cost   = coalesce(
    native sum(claude_code.cost.usage),
    hook  session.cost_usd      -- from transcript-tail estimate
)

authoritative_tokens = coalesce(
    native sum(claude_code.token.usage),
    hook  session.{input,output}_tokens
)

model = coalesce(
    native gen_ai.request.model (from claude_code.api_request),
    hook  gen_ai.request.model (from transcript tail)
)
```

Native always wins when present. Anthropic counts tokens authoritatively from the API response; our hook estimates from a bounded transcript tail. Both estimates may exist for the same session — `coalesce(native, hook)` picks the truthful one.

### Identity (user, cwd, repo)

Hook always wins. The native path doesn't see the developer's repo or cwd; it only sees what Claude Code chose to expose. Our hook stamps `code.cwd`, `vcs.repository.url.full`, `vcs.ref.head.name` as resource attributes from `git.Snapshot(cwd)`.

### Tool calls

Coalesce by `gen_ai.tool.call.id`:

- If both paths emitted for the same tool call: keep the **native** span (it has authoritative duration, retry count, MCP scope) but enrich it with `code.cwd` + `vcs.*` from the hook session's resource bundle.
- If only one side emitted: keep that one as-is.

### Edit decisions

Hook always wins — the hook sees the actual file diff context; native only sees the decision and `language`.

### Anti-double-count rule

`session_count`, `tool_call_count`, and `subagent_count` are rolled up **per `session.id`**, never per span. As long as the chat_id rollup folds both paths into the same `chat_id`, we don't double-count. The materializer's discovery query (`discoverCodingAgents`) already does this — confirm with:

```sql
SELECT
  coalesce(
    nullIf(ResourceAttributes['coding_agent.agent.parent_id'], ''),
    nullIf(SpanAttributes['coding_agent.agent.parent_id'], ''),
    SpanAttributes['coding_agent.session.id'],
    SpanAttributes['session.id']           -- Claude Code native
  ) AS chat_id,
  count() AS spans, uniqExact(coalesce(...)) AS distinct_sessions
FROM otel_traces
WHERE Timestamp >= now() - INTERVAL 24 HOUR
GROUP BY chat_id;
```

If `distinct_sessions > 1` for one `chat_id`, we have a dedupe leak. Fix by widening the coalesce in `CHAT_ID_EXPR`.

### Is coalesce good enough at scale?

Honest answer:

- Under ~1M spans/day per tenant: coalesce in queries is fine. ClickHouse evaluates the per-row coalesce in a few milliseconds; the query bottleneck is usually the wider session scan, not the attribute lookup.
- Over ~1M spans/day per tenant: we want a materialized view (`coding_agent_sessions`) that normalizes `claude_code.*` and `coding_agent.*` into one canonical row at ingest time. The view exists as a comment marker in `queries.ts` (the E1 deferral note). When we ship it, the change is single-file: point `OTEL_TRACES_TABLE` at the MV; the chat-id rollup logic stays the same.

Until then, every new attribute MUST be added to the coalesce expression in `queries.ts` so reads still work for both paths.

## 6. The `coding_agent.signal_source` marker

Every span MUST carry this attribute (resource-level, set by the adapter or inferred from `service.name` at query time). Values:

| Value | When |
| -- | -- |
| `hook` | OpenLit CLI emitted this span from a vendor hook event |
| `native` | The vendor's own OTel exporter emitted this span (e.g. Claude Code with `CLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_TELEMETRY=1`) |
| `sdk` | A regular OpenLit Go/Python SDK process (NOT a coding agent) |

Adapters MUST stamp `hook` explicitly. The query layer infers `native` from `service.name = 'claude-code'` AND absence of `coding_agent.signal_source`. The materializer's SDK discovery excludes anything that isn't `sdk` (a positive value of `hook` or `native` keeps the row off the SDK side).

## 7. Outcome enum mapping

Both vendors map onto the same six-value enum from `sdk/go/semconv/coding_agent.go`:

| Outcome | When (Cursor) | When (Claude Code hook) | When (Claude Code native) |
| -- | -- | -- | -- |
| `completed` | `outcome=completed` on sessionEnd | n/a (no equivalent signal) | n/a |
| `merged` | (no signal yet) | (no signal yet) | (no signal yet) |
| `committed` | (no signal yet) | (no signal yet) | (no signal yet) |
| `abandoned_no_change` | `outcome=abandoned` AND `!vcs.dirty` | SessionEnd `reason in [exit, logout]` AND `!vcs.dirty` | SessionEnd metric AND no recent commit AND clean tree |
| `abandoned_with_change` | `outcome=abandoned` AND `vcs.dirty` | SessionEnd `reason in [exit, logout]` AND `vcs.dirty` | SessionEnd metric AND dirty tree |
| `cancelled` | `outcome=cancelled` | SessionEnd `reason=clear` | (no signal yet) |

Never invent a new outcome value. Never leave outcome empty on a session-root span.

## 8. Capture-mode contract

Three modes apply identically across vendors. The matrix in `coding-agents-hook.mdc` §4 governs which attributes are allowed in each mode. Vendors do not get to widen capture beyond the global setting.

Special note on **bodies**:

- `gen_ai.input.messages` / `gen_ai.output.messages` / `gen_ai.tool.call.arguments` / `gen_ai.tool.call.result` / `coding_agent.llm.thought.text` / `coding_agent.tool.command` (full command) are body-bearing. They MUST be gated by `bodyAllowed(mode)` from `cli/internal/otlp/attrs.go`. Adapters that bypass this gate are bugs.

When Claude Code is configured to send native `OTEL_LOG_RAW_API_BODIES`, those bodies arrive under `claude_code.api_request_body.body` / `claude_code.api_response_body.body`. The query layer drops them in `minimal` and `metadata_only` modes via a `WHERE` filter — we trust the deployer's CLI config over what the vendor's native exporter chose to send.

## 9. Identity / privacy guardrails

These guardrails are absolute. No vendor adapter and no native-telemetry mapping may relax them.

1. **Cohort floor**. Per-user breakdowns suppress users with fewer than `COHORT_K_FLOOR` (default 5) sessions in the working window, unless the viewer is an admin. Apply this at query time in `queries.ts`, NEVER in the materializer.
2. **Email visibility**. `gen_ai.user.name` is the developer's email when OAuth is configured. It MUST be queryable for admins and MUST be masked behind the cohort floor for non-admins.
3. **Dispute trail**. Classification labels can be disputed via `POST /api/coding-agents/classification/dispute`. Disputed sessions are flagged but not deleted. Never re-classify a disputed session automatically — defer to the human reviewer.
4. **Body retention**. When `OPENLIT_CODING_CONTENT_CAPTURE != "full"`, no prompt body / tool result / file diff may land in `otel_traces`. The collector does not redact post-hoc; the adapter MUST gate at emit time.
5. **Cross-account leakage**. The `whereScope` helper in `queries.ts` enforces `organization.id` matching when `OPENLIT_REQUIRE_ORG_FILTER` is set. New queries MUST go through `whereScope`.

## 10. Adding a new vendor (worked example: opencode)

If we add OpenCode (or any other vendor):

1. **semconv** — add the vendor identifier to `sdk/go/semconv/coding_agent.go`'s vendor list AND to `src/client/src/types/agents.ts`'s `CodingAgentVendor` union. Run `go generate ./cli/...` to regenerate `cli/gen/semconv.ts`.
2. **Adapter** — create `cli/internal/coding/hook/opencode/handle.go`. Mirror the structure of `cursor/handle.go` or `claudecode/handle.go`. Map every payload key to the canonical attribute matrix in §2 — DO NOT introduce a new `opencode.*` namespace for facts that already have a canonical key.
3. **`peekContext`** — `cli/internal/coding/hook/hook.go`. Add the vendor's payload key names to `pickString`. The function MUST resolve `session_id`, `user`, `cwd`, `permission_mode`, `model`, and (when applicable) `parent_conversation_id` from this vendor's payload format.
4. **Plugin manifest** — `plugins/opencode/`. Mirror `plugins/cursor/` for VS-Code-style hooks or `plugins/claude-code/` for Anthropic-style. The plugin invokes `openlit coding hook --vendor=opencode --event=<EventName>`.
5. **Native telemetry mapping** — if the vendor ships its own OTel signals, write §4's equivalent for it. Add the inbound coalesce to `queries.ts` and document the dual-path rules.
6. **Icon** — add a tiny inline SVG component to `src/client/src/components/svg/coding-agents.tsx` and wire `case "opencode":` into `CodingAgentVendorIcon`. The hard-coded `=== "cursor"` checks in `coding-agents-table.tsx`, `signal-records.tsx`, and `trace-detail-page.tsx` should be replaced with a "ask the icon component, fall back to Bot" pattern so new vendors pick up icons automatically.
7. **Onboarding doc** — `docs/features/coding-agents/onboarding.mdx`. Add a tab for the vendor.
8. **Sanity check** — fire one session end to end, then run the verification SQL in `coding-agents-hook.mdc` §10.

## 11. Things the convention WILL bite you on

These are the rules that, when violated, make the UI silently render `0` / blank / wrong:

- Stamping cost as a string (`"0.15"` instead of `0.15`). The UI's `(row.cost ?? 0).toFixed(2)` returns `"NaN"` and we render `$NaN`.
- Stamping cost in cents (`15` for $0.15). Multiplies the dashboard total by 100.
- Stamping `gen_ai.system = "claude-code"`. The provider rollup over-counts Anthropic + misses correct provider attribution. Use `anthropic`.
- Stamping `coding_agent.session.outcome = ""`. The session-list query filters on outcome being one of the enum values; empty becomes "unknown" in the UI but breaks DORA-style queries.
- Forgetting to stamp `coding_agent.signal_source` AND `telemetry.distro.name = "openlit-cli"`. The materializer's SDK discovery picks the spans up as SDK telemetry and the agent detail page flips between layouts on refresh. Both stamps are mandatory and live in `cli/internal/otlp/exporter.go`. See `coding-agents-hook.mdc` §10 for the full three-barrier exclusion chain.
- Adding a vendor-namespaced attribute (`claude_code.foo`) that duplicates a canonical attribute (`coding_agent.foo`). The query layer reads canonical, the row will look empty even though the data is there.
- Inventing new outcome / decision / classification values. The UI checks are explicit enum comparisons; new values render as blank.
- Stamping ResourceAttributes with `service.name = "openlit-cli"`. Use the vendor identifier so the materializer's coding discovery picks it up. (The `openlit-cli` value goes on `telemetry.distro.name`, not on `service.name`.)
- **`ORDER BY agent_key` dedup trap**. `openlit_agents_summary` is a `ReplacingMergeTree(updated_at) ORDER BY agent_key`. Once a phantom row exists for the same agent_key but a different `source` value, FINAL picks whichever has the higher `updated_at` — which can flip back and forth across materialize ticks. The mitigation lives at the *write side* (three barriers in `discoverAgents`, see hook rule §10); the long-term schema fix is widening the ORDER BY to `(agent_key, source)` so SDK and coding rows can coexist for the same service.

## 12. Documented limitations (vendor data doesn't let us fold)

These are known limits where the data the vendor sends prevents perfect rollup. Do not pretend they're fixed; surface them to the operator instead.

- **Cursor: no stable chat-thread id across CLI processes**. When the user suspends a chat (laptop sleep, IDE restart) and resumes, Cursor spawns a fresh CLI process with a fresh `session_id` AND a fresh `conversation_id`. There is no field in the hook payload that links the new session to the previous one. Result: one user-perceived chat shows as N sessions in the OpenLit UI. The chat rollup is doing the right thing per the data it received; the limitation is upstream. Possible future fixes (in order of robustness): Cursor adds a `composer_thread_id` field to the payload, OR we read Cursor's local SQLite at `~/Library/Application Support/Cursor/User/globalStorage/state.vscdb` to map session_id → thread_id (version-fragile, not recommended without coordination with Cursor).
- **Claude Code: no `cwd` / `repo` in native OTel telemetry**. The native exporter only knows what Claude Code itself sees. When the user runs Claude Code outside a Git repo, or when `CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR` isn't set, those resource attributes will be empty even in the dual-path scenario.

When in doubt: grep for the canonical attribute name in `queries.ts` and `materialize.ts`. If a reader doesn't already coalesce your new key, your data will be invisible to the UI no matter how cleanly it lands in ClickHouse.
